'''''Spindizzy''''' is an [[isometric projection|isometric]] video game released for several [[8-bit]] home computers in 1986 by [[Electric Dreams Software]]. It combines [[Action game|action]] and [[Puzzle video game|puzzle video game]] elements. Players must navigate a series of screens to explore a landscape suspended in a three-dimensional space. Development was headed by Paul Shirley, who drew inspiration from [[Ultimate Play the Game]] games that feature an isometric projection.

The game was successful in the United Kingdom and was well received by the video game press. Reviewers praised its visuals and design, but criticized its audio. Similarities were drawn to ''[[Marble Madness]]'', which was released in arcades two years earlier. ''Spindizzy'' was followed by a 1990s sequel titled ''[[Spindizzy Worlds]]''.

== Gameplay ==
[[File:Spindizzy-Gameplay.png|thumb|left|alt=Horizontal rectangle video game screenshot that is a digital representation of a three dimensional path.|The player controls a probe to explore an [[Isometric projection|isometric]] stage. Game statistics (remaining time, collected jewels, and remaining stages) are tracked at the top. The [[ZX Spectrum]] version is pictured.]]

''Spindizzy'' is an [[Action game|action]] and [[Puzzle video game|puzzle game]] [[Video games with isometric graphics|played from an isometric perspective]]. Players can view the playing field from four angles, and rotate between them. The game takes place in a fictional landscape of interconnected stages suspended in a dimensional space.The player controls a probe called a Gyroscopic Environmental Reconnaissance And Land-Mapping Device (GERALD), via keyboard commands or a joystick. The craft is able to transform between three configurations: a ball, an inverted [[square pyramid]], and a [[gyroscope]], although the difference between each configuration is only visual. Players navigate the probe through the stages to explore the world within a time limit. The time limit can be extended by collecting power jewels scattered through the world and is decreased by falling off a stage. Stages feature ramps, corridors, and other obstacles that hinder the player from quickly traversing them. The game ends when time expires or the world is completely explored.<ref name="ZZAP-14">{{cite journal| journal = [[Zzap!64]]| title = ''Zzap! Test: Spindizzy''| publisher = [[Newsfield Publications]]| date = June 1986| issue = 14| pages = 108–109| url=https://archive.org/stream/zzap64-magazine-014/ZZap_64_Issue_014_1986_Jun#page/n107/mode/2up}}</ref><ref name="Crash-29">{{cite journal| journal = [[Crash (magazine)|Crash]]| publisher = [[Newsfield Publications]]| title = ''Spindizzy''| issue = 29| date = June 1986| pages = 16–17| url=https://archive.org/stream/Crash_No._29_1986-06_Newsfield_GB#page/n15/mode/2up}}</ref>

== Development and release ==

''Spindizzy'' was developed by Paul Shirley of British video game developer [[Electric Dreams Software]]. He was primarily inspired by [[Ultimate Play the Game]] games that feature an [[isometric projection]], but was also influenced by the gameplay of the 1984 arcade game ''[[Marble Madness]]''. Shirley created an [[Interpreter (computing)|interpreted]] script to generate the game's levels. The script allowed him to design a large number of stages using 11[[Kilobyte|KB]] of storage. The game was originally released for the [[Amstrad CPC]]<ref name='ace9'>{{cite magazine |title=The Third Dimension – Isometric 3D Games|magazine=ACE|issue=9|publisher=Future Publishing|date=June 1988|page=85|url=https://spectrumcomputing.co.uk/page.php?issue_id=1735&page=85|access-date=17 January 2023}}</ref> and later [[porting|ported]] to [[Apple II series|Apple II]], [[Atari 8-bit computers]], [[Commodore 64]] and [[ZX Spectrum]] computers.<ref name="Halcyon">{{cite book| title = [[Halcyon Days (book)|Halcyon Days]]: Interviews with Classic Computer and Video Games Programmers| editor = James Hague| year = 1997| chapter = Paul Shirley| publisher = Dadgum Games| chapter-url = https://dadgum.com/halcyon/BOOK/SHIRLEY.HTM}}</ref> Copies of ''Spindizzy'' were promoted as prizes in magazine contests upon its release.<ref>{{cite journal|date=July 1986|title=''Spindizzy'' Competition|url=https://archive.org/details/ComputerAndVideoGamesIssue057Jul86|journal=[[Computer and Video Games]]|publisher=[[EMAP]]|issue=57|page=[https://archive.org/details/ComputerAndVideoGamesIssue057Jul86/page/n30 72]}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=August 1986|title=A Really Rather Big Competition|url=https://archive.org/details/your-sinclair-08|journal=[[Your Sinclair]]|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|issue=8|pages=[https://archive.org/details/your-sinclair-08/page/n39 38]–39}}</ref> American video game company [[Activision]] published the game in the United States as part of its "Electric Dreams" series.<ref name="Compute-77">{{cite journal|last=Bateman|first=Selby|date=October 1986|title=A Great Year For Games|url=https://archive.org/details/1986-10-compute-magazine/page/n19/mode/2up|journal=[[Compute!]]|publisher=[[Small System Services]]|issue=77|page=18}}</ref> John Sanderson programmed the Apple II version; Shirley was unaware of the port's existence until the mid-1990s.<ref name="Halcyon"/><ref name="Moby">{{cite web| url = http://www.mobygames.com/game/spindizzy| title = ''Spindizzy'' – MobyGames| publisher = [[MobyGames]]| access-date = 2010-01-18}}</ref> ''Spindizzy'' was later re-released as part of an Activision compilation.<ref>{{cite journal|date=April 1991|title=''Spindizzy''|url=https://archive.org/details/your-sinclair-64/page/n7/mode/2up|journal=[[Your Sinclair]]|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|issue=64|page=8}}</ref> The company sold ''Spindizzy''{{'}}s compilation rights not long after obtaining them, which reduced the amount of royalties to Shirley and Electric Dreams. Shirley eventually severed the contract with Activision, citing late royalty payments among other actions he disagreed with.<ref name="Halcyon"/>

