Shirley described the game's marketing life as short and attributed that to Activision's business practices. James Hague of Dadgum Games commented that ''Spindizzy'' could have been an "all-time classic" had it received a proper marketing campaign.<ref name="Halcyon"/> Despite this, ''Spindizzy'' sold well in the United Kingdom<ref name="Compute-77"/> reaching the number one position in the Amstrad charts in March 1986.<ref name='pcwcharts100486'>{{cite magazine |title=Charts|magazine=Popular Computing Weekly|issue=15|publisher=Sunshine Publications|date=10 April 1986|page=35|url=https://spectrumcomputing.co.uk/page.php?issue_id=2903&page=27|access-date=17 January 2023}}</ref> The Commodore and Spectrum versions also reached their Top 10 charts on their release several weeks later, taking the game to the number 2 position in the all formats chart.<ref name='pcwcharts150586'>{{cite magazine |title=Charts|magazine=Popular Computing Weekly|issue=20|publisher=Sunshine Publications|date=15 May 1986|page=46|url=https://spectrumcomputing.co.uk/page.php?issue_id=2908&page=46|access-date=17 January 2023}}</ref><ref name='pcwcharts220586'>{{cite magazine |title=Charts|magazine=Popular Computing Weekly|issue=21|publisher=Sunshine Publications|date=22 May 1986|page=46|url=https://spectrumcomputing.co.uk/page.php?issue_id=2909&page=46|access-date=17 January 2023}}</ref>

The game was well received by video game journalists upon its release. ''[[Zzap!64]]'' awarded ''Spindizzy'' a Gold Medal.<ref name="ZZAP-14"/> Tony Hetherington of ''[[Computer Gamer]]'' listed it as one of the essential Spectrum titles of 1986.<ref name="CG-17">{{cite journal|last=Hetherington|first=Tony|date=August 1986|title=The Spectrum Collection Update|url=https://archive.org/details/Computer_Gamer_Issue_17_1986-08_Argus_Press_GB|journal=[[Computer Gamer]]|publisher=[[Argus Press|Argus Specialist Publications]]|issue=17|page=[https://archive.org/details/Computer_Gamer_Issue_17_1986-08_Argus_Press_GB/page/n68 14]}}</ref>

Praise from reviewers focused on the game's visuals and design, while criticism focused on the audio. Three of ''Zzap!64''{{'}}s reviewers—[[Julian Rignall]], [[Gary Liddon]], and [[Gary Penn]]—called the graphics "amazing", well-executed, and "varied"; but they described the audio as sparse. Rignall and Penn complimented the challenging gameplay and commented that its addictiveness outweighed any frustration experienced while playing. The three summarized by urging readers to purchase the game.<ref name="ZZAP-14"/> ''Computer Gamer'' reviewer Mike Roberts praised ''Spindizzy''{{'}}s gameplay, but mentioned that the screen's orientation can require a period of adjustment, particularly when using a [[joystick]].<ref name="CG-13">{{cite journal|last=Roberts|first=Mike|date=April 1986|title=''Spindizzy''|url=https://archive.org/details/Computer_Gamer_Issue_13_1986-04_Argus_Press_GB/page/n29/mode/2up|journal=[[Computer Gamer]]|publisher=[[Argus Press|Argus Specialist Publications]]|issue=13|pages=30–31}}</ref> ''Crash''{{'}}s reviewer called ''Spindizzy'' "one of the most addictive" ZX Spectrum games, noting its innovative use of shape changing, multiple view angles, and speed control. The audio was seen as lacking compared to the rest of the game, but was still described as good.<ref name="Crash-29"/> Phil South of ''Your Sinclair'' gave the game high marks for graphics, playability, value for money, and addictiveness. He praised the ability to change viewpoints and the realistic movements of the character sprite. He also lauded the speed and quality of the graphics.<ref name="YS-7">{{cite journal| journal = [[Your Sinclair]]| publisher = [[Dennis Publishing]]| title = ''Spindizzy''| date = July 1986| issue = 7| pages = 60–61| first = Phil| last = South| url=https://archive.org/stream/your-sinclair-07/YourSinclair_07_July_1986#page/n61/mode/2up}}</ref> ''[[Info (magazine)|Info]]'' assessed the Commodore 64 version four stars out of five, recommending it as "a hot little number with much of the appeal of ''Marble Madness''" but better.<ref name="info198701">{{Cite magazine |last1=Dunnington |first1=Benn |last2=Brown |first2=Mark R. |last3=Malcolm |first3=Tom |date=January–February 1987 |title=64/128 Gallery |url=https://archive.org/stream/info-magazine-13/Info_Issue_13_1987_Jan-Feb#page/n13/mode/2up |magazine=Info |pages=14–21}}</ref> Roy Wagner reviewed the game for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'', stating that ''Spindizzy'' "has a lot to offer and is an excellent value."<ref name="CGW34">{{cite magazine |last=Wagner |first=Roy |title=Commodore Key |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=January–February 1987 |volume=1 |issue=34 |pages=39}}</ref>

Reviewers drew comparisons to ''Marble Madness'', which was ported to home platforms the same year. Roberts called ''Spindizzy'' the "best 'marble' game yet",<ref name="CG-13"/> and [[Charles Ardai]] of ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' called it "a thoroughly enjoyable game" superior to ''Marble Madness''.<ref name="ardai198707">{{cite magazine|last=Ardai|first=Charles|authorlink=Charles Ardai|url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/issues/cgw_38.pdf|title=Titans of the Computer Gaming World / Part Three of Five: Ardai on Activision|date=June–July 1987|magazine=[[Computer Gaming World]]|issue=38|pages=36}}</ref> South described ''Spindizzy'' as the "closest thing yet to ''Marble Madness''" on the ZX Spectrum, while Liddon said that any similarities to ''Marble Madness'' were coincidental.<ref name="ZZAP-14"/><ref name="YS-7"/> Many publications commented that the game was obviously inspired by ''Marble Madness''.<ref name="Crash-29"/><ref>{{cite journal|date=July 1986|title=''Spindizzy''|url=https://archive.org/details/ZX-computing-1986-07|journal=ZX Computing Monthly|publisher=[[Argus Press|Argus Specialist Publications]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/ZX-computing-1986-07/page/n64 65]|editor=Bryan Ralph}}</ref><ref name="YS-6">{{cite journal| journal = [[Your Sinclair]]| publisher = [[Dennis Publishing]]| title = Frontlines| date = June 1986| issue = 6| page = 13| url=https://archive.org/stream/your-sinclair-06/YourSinclair_06_Jun_1986#page/n13/mode/2up}}</ref><ref name="Retro-53">{{cite journal|last=Grannell|first=Craig|date=August 2008|title=The Making of ''Marble Madness''|url=https://archive.org/stream/retro_gamer/RetroGamer_053#page/n81/mode/2up|journal=[[Retro Gamer]]|publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]]|issue=53|pages=82–87}}</ref> In 1993, ''[[Commodore Force]]'' ranked the game at number ten on its list of the top 100 Commodore 64 games.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top Ton!|url=https://archive.org/stream/zzap64-magazine-101/ZZap_64_Issue_101_Commodore_Force_Issue_11_1993_Autumn#page/n32/mode/1up/|website=Commodore Force|date=Autumn 1993|accessdate=2017-09-03|page=33}}</ref>

More than a decade later, reviews still praised the game. [[Allgame]] editor Ryan Glover called ''Spindizzy'' an "innovative puzzler" that prompts players to fully explore it.<ref name="Allgame">{{cite web| url = http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=4757| title = ''Spindizzy'' – Overview| publisher = [[Allgame]]| first = Ryan| last = Glover| access-date = 2010-01-16| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141115031717/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=4757| archive-date = 2014-11-15}}</ref> Saying that the game successfully mixed infuriating moments with brilliant design, Darran Jones of ''[[Retro Gamer]]'' called ''Spindizzy'' a "timeless classic".<ref name="RG-52">{{cite journal|last=Jones|first=Darran|title=Retrorevival: ''Spindizzy''|url=https://archive.org/stream/retro_gamer/RetroGamer_052#page/n19/mode/2up|journal=[[Retro Gamer]]|publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]]|issue=52|page=22}}</ref> The magazine rated ''Spindizzy'' the second best game with an isometric perspective, citing its presentation and stage designs.<ref name="RG-59">{{cite journal|title=Top 25 Isometric Games|url=https://archive.org/stream/retro_gamer/RetroGamer_059#page/n71/mode/2up|journal=[[Retro Gamer]]|publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]]|issue=59|page=73}}</ref> Over 25 years after its release, ''Retro Gamer'' staff called the game "intensely devious and addictive", adding that "''Spindizzy''{{'}}s only enemy was yourself".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mason|first=Graeme|date=July 2012|title=From the Archives – Electric Dreams|url=https://archive.org/stream/retro_gamer/RetroGamer_104#page/n83/mode/2up|location=[[Bournemouth]]|publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]]|issue=104|page=84|issn=1742-3155|oclc=489477015|journal=[[Retro Gamer]]}}</ref>

''Spindizzy''{{'}}s isometric design partially inspired Glenn Corpes during the development of the 1989 title ''[[Populous (video game)|Populous]]''.<ref name="Edge-107">{{cite magazine|author=Edge Staff|date=February 2002|title=The Making Of: ''Populous''|url=http://www.next-gen.biz/features/making-populous|url-status=dead|magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]|publisher=[[Future plc|Future Publishing]]|issue=107|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710085757/http://www.edge-online.com/features/making-populous|archive-date=July 10, 2012|access-date=2010-01-17}}</ref> Activision released a sequel titled ''[[Spindizzy Worlds]]'' for [[Amiga]] and [[Atari ST]] computers in 1990.<ref name="Halcyon"/> The game features similar gameplay, but improved graphics and larger playing fields.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Webb|first=Trenton|date=January 1991|title=Screenplay: ''Spindizzy Worlds''|url=https://archive.org/details/amigaformatmagazine-018|journal=[[Amiga Format]]|publisher=[[Future Publishing]]|issue=18|pages=[https://archive.org/details/amigaformatmagazine-018/page/n181 82]–84}}</ref> It was later ported to the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]] by [[ASCII (company)|ASCII]], which Shirley disapproved of and considered it a "disaster". He took legal action over the span of several years to obtain royalty information and payments.<ref name="Halcyon"/>

